								<div class="title" id="post-title-2082258">
																		SCP&#039;s and IQ (Bonus discussion on personality tests as well)
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tim-scriven" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1944047); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1944047&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226578" alt="Tim Scriven" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1944047)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tim-scriven" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1944047); return false;" >Tim Scriven</a></span> <span class="odate time_1407309778 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Aug 2014 07:22</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2082258">
									

<p>Okay, so I've not yet posted a successful SCP here. I have however read a lot of SCP's, and happen to know a lot about intelligence testing. I've been bothered by the way authors throw around the concept of IQ testing. Personally I think its probably never a good idea to mention an IQ result in your SCP article, but if you are going to, keep this in mind: IQ tests are highly specialised instruments, if you are going to talk about them you will have to do some (brief) scholarly research on how they work first. The same goes for personality tests. Here are some quick points to get you thinking.</p>
<p>I spent six months working as a research assistant in this area, but I wrote this in haste and haven't engaged with the literature in about two years. Its your responsibility to double check everything before you use it as advice.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1. IQ testing is probably not really what you are looking for to describe your SCP's intellect</p>
<p>A lot of authors want to establish their SCP is smart, so its understandable that they reach into the cultural vocabulary and pull out &quot;IQ test&quot; as a way to demonstrate that. However:</p>
<p>A ) Most IQ tests load on verbal skills and cultural knowledge. There are exceptions (such as Raven's progressive matrices), but for the most part IQ tests aren't fair on those who don't speak the language they are administered in as a native language.<br />
B ) Performance in IQ tests can be impaired by a variety of factors that many SCP's experience, such as deep depression or agitation.<br />
C ) IQ tests are not an appropriate measure of sapience, computer programs that are &quot;good&quot; at many different types of question common to IQ tests (including matrices and verbal analogies) have been created.<br />
D ) Because IQ tests are normed relative to a population, saying that your SCP has an IQ much above 180 (as a rule of thumb and assuming the standard deviation of the test is about 16) is a bit meaningless.<br />
E ) IQ tests tell you nothing or little about whether a person is a &quot;genius&quot; in the colloquial sense of the word. Plenty of people with very high IQ's have very little interesting to say and minimal creative achievements. Conversely, people who are commonly regarded as geniuses may have IQ's not that far above average, or even a bit below average.<br />
F) There's no clear correlation between capacity for interpersonal manipulation and IQ.</p>
<p>2. IQ tests are based on population norms. It is also very unclear whether they are any good or not and most research psychologists have a healthy dose of skepticism about them.</p>
<p>(^long section title that one)</p>
<p>Originally IQ results were defined by the formula (Mental age / Chronological age) * 100, so a four year old who performed like a six year old would have an IQ of 150. In order to generalise the tests to adults, norms were made statistical instead. In practice that means that an IQ score is worked out as followed:</p>
<p>*Assume intelligence is distributed according to a bell curve.</p>
<p>*Pick a standard deviation (some tests place it at 15, others at 16, some at 20)</p>
<p>*Pick a mean result (this is almost always 100)</p>
<p>*Work out (guesstimate) the person's ranking in the population as a whole based on their score, comparing it to prior samples of the population to work out how common a score like that is.</p>
<p>Using assumption 1, and the selected numbers chosen to be the standard deviation and mean, assign them a score given that we know their ranking.</p>
<p>Say the standard deviation is 16, the following is roughly how common different scores will be:</p>
<p>116- around one in five.<br />
132- around one in fifty<br />
148- Around one in 600<br />
164- Around one in 30,000</p>
<p>That's me doing the Z score maths in my head and from memory, so consult an actual statistical table instead of relying on it. The main point I want to make is that higher scores get rare fast. An upshot of that is that since IQ tests are normed through comparison to a very finite group of people, most IQ tests don't go up very far at all. When I read of a super-computing AI, for example, said to have an IQ of 250, I have very little idea what that is supposed to mean. Does it mean that the IQ test was normed in such a way that we know that only one in a trillion normal humans would get that result?</p>
<p>There are many difficulties in this process. One of the big ones is selecting the right problems to be scored, since this will determine the nature of the IQ the test determines. Imagine the test asked lots of questions like &quot;what is the difference between a yacht and a boat&quot; for example, that would mean that it favoured the rich over the poor (that's not a hypothetical, the American SAT, basically an IQ test, used to include a bunch of questions just like that).</p>
<p>Detractors of IQ tests argue the problems selected are pretty arbitrary. Defenders of IQ tests argue that they can be validated in a number of ways, such as their correlation with work performance and school and college grades. It's a complicated debate, and I have my own view which is very qualified and somewhere in the middle.</p>
<p>3. IQ tests usually have discrete components</p>
<p>IQ tests will usually output a bunch of data not just one whether or not a person is intelligent, but in what way are they intelligent. The most common division is between crystallised intelligence (culturally relevant knowledge, such as knowing what the word 'abhorrent' means, or being able to answer Rat:Mammal as Python is to &#8230;?) and fluid intelligence (problem solving which requires no prior knowledge, or at least is supposed to require no prior knowledge.) Sometimes the division is between &quot;verbal&quot; intelligence and &quot;performance&quot; intelligence instead. Most SCP articles which give an IQ score would be better off giving one or more component scores.</p>
<p>4. Personality tests</p>
<p>The bad:</p>
<p>A) Almost all researchers think the Myers Briggs is absolute rubbish. It's highly unlikely the foundation would use it.<br />
B) Even many researchers working directly on the concept of emotional intelligence do not think it is very good. It's pretty unlikely the foundation would use it.</p>
<p>The good:</p>
<p>A) By far the most commonly used personality metric is the big five. Assuming the foundation ever uses personality tests, they would definitely use this one.<br />
B) The PEN model (psychotism, neuroticism and extroversion) is also pretty good and is often used for assessment of criminals in particular, so lot of potential SCP tie ins.<br />
C) There are a huge number of tests that have been created individual differences psychologists (its sort of what they do) a lot could be integrated really well into an SCP article.</p>
<p>5. Final comment- show don't tell.</p>
<p>If you want to convince the reader that your SCP is intelligent or has such and such a personality trait, the use of IQ tests and personality tests might, in some instances, be what you are looking for. On the whole though they seem like a way of &quot;telling&quot; the reader something about your SCP that should probably be &quot;shown&quot; through their behaviour. Sometimes it is better to tell rather than to show (especially given the format of the wiki which is far more clinical, scientific and focused on quantities than most narratives) , but there is a good reason why &quot;show don't tell&quot; has become an authorial adage, and it's worth having it in mind. It's fine to break standard rules of writing, but you should know those rules, and you should have a clear understanding of why you are breaking them.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><em>Collapsed the wall of text, since this is a forum post. Definitely consider putting this on a sandbox page for ease of reading. -Zyn</em></p>

