					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226578" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1544515651 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Dec 2018 08:07</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4082720">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Most people are a conglomerate abilities so this could help make a better psychological profile.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Possibly, although some readers aren't familiar with what the numbers mean (you'd be surprised how many people think an IQ of 100 is high) or how the types of intelligence sections are supposed to be used.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>In scenarios similar to these they could help with immersion/characterization.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It also runs the risk of people just treating the categories as stats on a D&amp;D-esque character sheet.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This way you could address the talents of various sentient entities. Say a multi-dimensional entity is tested at a 100 IQ but is brought down by a language barrier and excels in spatial awareness.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This kind of begs the question of why the Foundation administered a multi-dimensional entity (not a human) an already fairly problematic test battery to begin with, and why the entity was so obliging as to complete the entire test.</p>
<p>Granted, tests of intelligence/knowledge can definitely be mentioned successfully in articles, but one shouldn't feel obligated to shoehorn them in to confirm or exaggerate an entity's intelligence. Unless an anomaly/article premise is ultimately closely focused on these sorts of tests, adding some extra numbers and category buzzwords doesn't do a ton for characterization or immersion.</p>

							</div>

								
					
