					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tim-scriven" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1944047); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1944047&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226578" alt="Tim Scriven" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1944047)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tim-scriven" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1944047); return false;" >Tim Scriven</a></span> <span class="odate time_1407544287 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Aug 2014 00:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2084592">
									

<p>I guess the point is that if the foundation works on currently accepted best scientific practice unless they have additional information which the scientific community doesn't (which sounds like it would be their safest bet by far) they wouldn't treat Freudian psychology as fact. The odd experimenter or two might venture a hypothesis in Freudian terms, but they would not present it as fact. As it is there are SCP's (even quite good SCP's like the all-mother) that refer to things like Opedial complexes as if they are definitely a real thing, and that's just sloppy methodology in my opinion.</p>

							</div>

								
					
